ese encounters. Religious concerns, ethnicity, gender and other social factors central to identity formation were often intertwined and they yielded different ways of drawing the limits of tolerance and intolerance. This book enhances our understanding of the formative centuries of Jewish and Christian religious traditions. It also brings the results of historical inquiry into dialogue with present-day questions of religious tolerance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 4aAntiquity. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aearly Judaism, early Christianity, tolerance, intolerance, religious recognition.1 aDowling, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunderberg, Ismo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarjanmaa, Sami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabahn, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabahn, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLehtipuu, Outi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehtipuu, Outi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevine, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiddleton, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNikki, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRafael, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRokem, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYuval, Israel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g